      <hedline>
        <hl1>Certified Teachers</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Daniel A Simon letter warns that forcing newly certified teachers into toughest schools will make it even harder for New York City to attract and retain qualified instructors (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Deal Is Struck on Placement of Instructors; Certified Teachers to Go to Worst Schools in City'' (news article, Aug. 25):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Deal Is Struck on Placement of Instructors; Certified Teachers to Go to Worst Schools in City'' (news article, Aug. 25):</p>
        <p>This decision means that a new, qualified, but inexperienced teacher looking for a job will know that New York City would place her in one of its toughest schools. What potential recruit would want to take that deal?</p>
        <p>Surely this settlement will only make it harder for the city, already short of certified teachers, to attract and retain qualified teachers. It is a mystery why the state education commissioner, Richard P. Mills, who brought the suit, considers this approach to be sound education policy.</p>
        <p>DANIEL A. SIMON  New York, Aug. 28, 2000</p>
      </block>
